msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:4
msgid "# Autonav"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:6
msgid "Your ship is equipped with an Automatic Navigation system, usually abbreviated as Autonav."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:7
msgid "This system allows your ship to automatically go to target locations, land on planets, follow ships, and even fly along routes to far away systems."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:9
msgid "Autonav can be triggered several different ways, but the main way is by opening the overlay map with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"overlay\")..\"#0\" %> key, and then right-clicking to go to a location."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:10
msgid "You can also double-click on a space object such as a planet to land on it, double-click on a jump point to use it, or right-click on a selected pilot to automatically follow them."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:12
msgid "You can also activate autonav directly from the [star map](mechanics/map) by selecting a system and clicking on the #bAutonav#0 button to go to it."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:14
msgid "## Settings"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:16
msgid "Autonav settings can be modified from the #binformation window#0 that you can open with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"info\")..\"#0\" %> key."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:17
msgid "Afterwards, click on the #bsettings#0 button from the main tab."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/autonav.md:19
msgid "You can control many aspects of the behaviour, such as whether or not you follow pilots that jump or land, whether or not you move along the patrol lanes, or whether you match speed with the slowest ship in your fleet, among other options."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:2
msgid "Bioships"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:5
msgid "# Bioships"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:7
msgid "Bioships are a hybrid between man-made constructs and living animals, and are tamed and created by the [Soromid Tribes](lore/factions/soromid)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:8
msgid "Unlike normal ships, bioships have built-in cores that grow stronger as the ship gains experience."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:9
msgid "Experience is gained primarily through doing missions with the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:10
msgid "By gaining experience, a bio-ship will be able to increase its rank."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:11
msgid "Other than improving the core outfits, ranks allow the ship to learn new skills and become significantly more powerful."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:13
msgid "## Skills"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:15
msgid "Bioship skills, ranks, and other information can be seen from the #bInformation window#0, which can be opened with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"info\")..\"#0\" %> key."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/bioships.md:16
msgid "You can also reset the skills by using experience, although this can lower your rank."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:2
msgid "Boarding Ships"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:4
msgid "# Boarding"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:6
msgid "You can board [disabled](mechanics/damage) ships by getting close to them and matching speed with them."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:7
msgid "This can be automated by using your ship's builtin autonav functionality (by pressing the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"approach\")..\"#0\" %> key)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:8
msgid "Once you board the ship, an interface will open that will let you interact with the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:10
msgid "Possible actions include looting, stealing outfits, or trying to capture the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:12
msgid "Possible actions include looting, or stealing outfits."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:15
msgid "## Looting"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:17
msgid "You can steal credits, fuel, cargo, and outfits from ships you board."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:18
msgid "Looting anything from a ship will lower your reputation with the faction to which the ship belongs."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:19
msgid "This may also make nearby ships angry if they dislike your action."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:21
msgid "The amount of loot available is determined by your **Boarding Bonus** modifier."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:22
msgid "Higher values will allow you to obtain more loot from the ships you board."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:24
msgid "## Stealing Outfits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:26
msgid "The outfits that you can steal from a ship are random, and the number is influenced by your **Boarding Bonus** modifier."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:27
msgid "Higher modifier values will let you steal more outfits from a ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:28
msgid "The cost of repairing a stolen outfit is the base cost multiplied by `(10 + their crew) / (10 + your crew)`."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:31
msgid "## Capturing"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:33
msgid "Capturing a ship is a three stage process:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:35
msgid "1. Board and Capture the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:36
msgid "1. Escort the ship to a spaceport with refuelling capabilities."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:37
msgid "1. Pay to repair the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:39
msgid "The cost of repairing a captured ship is the ship's cost, including equipped outfits, multiplied by `(10 + their crew) / (10 + your crew) + 0.25`."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:40
msgid "Additionally, factions do not take kindly to your trying to capture their ships, and you will suffer a large reputation hit when trying to capture ships belonging to any faction."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/boarding.md:41
msgid "Once you successfully capture the ship, you will obtain it, outfits and all, and be able to either use it yourself or [deploy it as an escort](mechanics/playerfleet)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:2
msgid "Cargo"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:4
msgid "# Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:6
msgid "Cargo plays an important role in spacefaring, be it for cargo deliveries, or for capturing objects of value."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:7
msgid "Each ship has a maximum amount of cargo it can carry, and a [mass limit](mechanics/mass) that decreases mobility if surpassed."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:9
msgid "## Obtaining Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:11
msgid "Cargo may be obtained from the #bCommodity Exchange#0 found on many spaceports."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:12
msgid "It can also be obtained from missions, [mining](mechanics/mining), or [pillaging](mechanics/boarding)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:14
msgid "## Cargo Inertia"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:16
msgid "The **Cargo Inertia** property determines how much real mass gets added to your ship per mass of cargo, and represents how efficient the ship is at carrying cargo."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:17
msgid "For example, with -50% Cargo Inertia, 100 tonnes of cargo would only add 50 tonnes of mass to your ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:19
msgid "## Managing Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:21
msgid "You can manage your cargo from the cargo tab of the information menu that you can open with <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"info\")..\"#0\" %>."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:22
msgid "Cargo can be dumped from both space and while landed using the cargo menu."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:24
msgid "### Mission Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:26
msgid "If you dump mission cargo, it will abort the mission and may have consequences in some cases."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:28
msgid "### Illegal Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:30
msgid "Some cargo may be illegal to different factions."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:31
msgid "The illegality status will be displayed in the cargo menu."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:32
msgid "If a faction scans you and finds you have illegal cargo, you will likely face consequences."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:35
msgid "### Fleet Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:37
msgid "If you have more than one ship in [your fleet](mechanics/playerfleet), your cargo will be distributed throughout all your ships, although it will start by filling your ship first."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:38
msgid "If a ship carrying cargo is destroyed, you will lose that cargo."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/cargo.md:39
msgid "Mission cargo can only be carried on your ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/credits.md:2
msgid "Credits"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/credits.md:4
msgid "# Credits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/credits.md:6
msgid "The economy is based on the universal currency known as credits and represented with the ¤ symbol."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/credits.md:7
msgid "Credits are cryptographic-based and stored on credsticks, which are very small and easy to carry."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/credits.md:8
msgid "You can obtain credits by doing [missions](mechanics/missions), [pillaging ships](mechanics/boarding), or [trading](mechanics/trading)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:2
msgid "Damage"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:4
msgid "# Damage"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:6
msgid "Weapons deal damage to lower the shields and armour of enemy ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:7
msgid "If the target ship has shields up, damage is first dealt to shields."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:8
msgid "When shields are down, damage will be dealt to armour."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:9
msgid "Finally, when the target ship reaches 0 armour, it will be destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:11
msgid "Apart from standard damage, weapons can deal disable damage, which instead of hurting armour, it applies stress, which can disable the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:12
msgid "Disabled ships [can be boarded](mechanics/boarding)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:14
msgid "## Absorption and Penetration"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:16
msgid "Absorption reduces the amount of damage taken by a ship by a percentage amount."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:17
msgid "However, this reduction can be nullified by penetration, which is directly subtracted from the absorption."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:18
msgid "Note that penetration can not increase the damage past 100%, and absorption can only reduce the damage to 0%."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:20
msgid "## Disable Damage and Stress"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:22
msgid "Disable damage is the only way to disable ships, by applying stress."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:23
msgid "When a ship's stress is larger than the available armour, it becomes disabled, and [can be boarded](mechanics/boarding)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:24
msgid "Unlike regular damage, disable damage can penetrate shields, however, it suffers a large penalty when shields are up."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:25
msgid "In particular, it will deal 50% stress when the target has 100% shields, and 100% stress when the target has 0% shields."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:26
msgid "Disable damage is also affected by absorption and penetration."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:28
msgid "## Damage Types"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:30
msgid "There are different damage types that differentiate how much damage is done to shields versus armour, and the amount of knockback."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:31
msgid "For example, kinetic damage does 80% damage to shields, 115% damage to armour, and 100% knockback."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:32
msgid "On the other hand, ion damage does 130% damage to shields, 80% damage to armour, and has 10% knockback."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:33
msgid "Using the best damage type can play a critical role in winning fights."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:35
msgid "## Shields Down and Regeneration"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:37
msgid "When a ship's shields get knocked offline, it takes 5 seconds for the shields to start regenerating again, and can be reduced with lower **Shield Down Time**."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:38
msgid "Any damage during this window will restart the time it takes to regenerate shields."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/damage.md:39
msgid "When shields get back up there they will regenerate faster during the first 3 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/effects.md:2
msgid "Effects"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/effects.md:4
msgid "# Effects"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/effects.md:6
msgid "Ships can be affected by different effects that can be either beneficial or detrimental."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/effects.md:7
msgid "Although effects are usually applied through outfits, such as being hit by weapon fire or triggering some outfit, they can also be applied from other sources."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/effects.md:8
msgid "Effects applied to your ship are visible at the top of the GUI with effects in #Fgreen#0 indicating beneficial effects, while those in #Hred#0 indicate detrimental effects."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/effects.md:9
msgid "Some types of effects can stack multiple types, which will be indicated by a number on the icon indicating how many stacks there are, while others will get refreshed when reapplied."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/energy.md:2
msgid "Energy"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/energy.md:4
msgid "# Energy"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/energy.md:6
msgid "Energy is used to power weapons and other outfits."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/energy.md:7
msgid "A ship will generate a flat amount of energy per second."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:2
msgid "Equipment"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:4
msgid "# Equipment"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:6
msgid "Outfits play a significant role in a ship's success at whatever activity it may attempt to do."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:7
msgid "Each ship has a fixed number of slots with different properties"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:9
msgid "## Slots"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:11
msgid "There are fundamentally four different types of slots a ship can have:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:13
msgid "1. **Weapons**: Used for causing damage and attacking ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:14
msgid "1. **Utilities**: Provides special or conditional abilities."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:15
msgid "1. **Structurals**: Used for changing core stats of the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:16
msgid "1. **Cores**: Can be either for hulls, engines, or systems and are required to be equipped for the ship to be space-worthy."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:18
msgid "Furthermore, slots can have special properties such as:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:20
msgid "1. **Fighter Bays**: Modifies weapon slots, allowing the installation of fighter bays, and in some cases, do not allow equipping normal weapons."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:21
msgid "1. **Accessories**: A special slot that only allows equipping accessory-type outfits."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:23
msgid "## Equipment Window"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:25
msgid "The equipment window is available when [landing](mechanics/landing) on spaceports with refuelling capabilities."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:26
msgid "It allows you to not only change ships but also to change the outfits the ship has equipped."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:27
msgid "You can also see updated statistics and properties of the ships you own."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:29
msgid "Additionally, you can control what ships are currently deployed to define your fleet."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:32
msgid "### Auto-Equipping"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:34
msgid "The equipment window also has autoequipping functionality."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:35
msgid "Although it does not change the core outfits, by clicking the \"Autoequip\" button, it will remove non-core outfits and try to find a suitable configuration for the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:36
msgid "There is some randomness in the process, so every time you click the button, you will get a slightly different configuration."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:37
msgid "This can be used to get a ship ready to fly quickly."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:39
msgid "## Intrinsic Outfits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:41
msgid "Intrinisc outfits are modifications to the ship itself that do not take an outfit slot."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:42
msgid "They are usually much more difficult to obtain, as they require extensive modifications to the ship itself."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:43
msgid "Once installed, in general, they can not be removed nor moved to another ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/equipment.md:44
msgid "You can view the intrinsic outfits a ship has from the equipment window when [landed](mechanics/landing) at a spaceport with refuelling capabilities."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:2
msgid "Electronic Warfare"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:4
msgid "# Electronic Warfare"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:6
msgid "A large part of combat is not only direct damage, but electronic warfare between the evasive and sensing abilities of ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:7
msgid "Electronic warfare plays a large role in determining when ships are seen, how well weapons track or lock onto ships, and stealth abilities of ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:8
msgid "There are fundamentally three different levels, from coarse to fine:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:10
msgid "1. Detection and hiding"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:11
msgid "2. Signature and tracking"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:12
msgid "3. Stealth"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:14
msgid "All electronic warfare values are based on distances, since they represent the distance at which the ship is fully detected."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:16
msgid "## Scanning"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:18
msgid "Whenever you target a ship, your ship will begin performing a scan on it."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:19
msgid "This is indicated by the rotating icon on the ship tab that appears in your ship's interface."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:20
msgid "When the icon stops rotating, it indicates that the ship has been scanned."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:21
msgid "By pressing the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"scan\")..\"#0\" %> key, you can call up the information about the scanned ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:22
msgid "This will show you information such as the outfits the ship has and the cargo it is carrying."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:24
msgid "Similarly, other ships will scan your ship when targeting it."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:25
msgid "This is usually not a problem, however, if you are carrying outfits or commodities that are illegal to the faction of the ship scanning you, it may bring repercussions."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:26
msgid "Ships scanning you are shown on the overlay and if you have illegal items, it will temporarily stop [autonav](mechanics/autonav)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:28
msgid "## Detection and Hiding"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:30
msgid "Without modifiers, ships are detected based on [their mass](mechanics/mass)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:31
msgid "In particular, they are detected at a distance of `mass^(1.0/1.8) * 350` which amounts to about 6,513 km for a Llama with 193 tonnes of mass, or 43,278 km for a Goddard with 5,834 tonnes of mass."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:32
msgid "This value gets reduced by the **Detection** bonus of the detecting ship, and multiplied by the **Detection Range** of the ship being detected."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:33
msgid "Since this value determines the base signature and stealth values of the ship, it can play a significant role in electronic warfare."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:35
msgid "### Detecting Space Objects and Jumps"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:37
msgid "For detecting general objects such as jump points or asteroids, the detection distance has a base value of <%= constant( \"EW_JUMPDETECT_DIST\", \"distance\" ) %>."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:38
msgid "This distance can be modified by values such as how well hidden the jump is."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:39
msgid "For space objects such as planets or stations the base value is <%= constant( \"EW_SPOBDETECT_DIST\", \"distance\" ) %>, subject to the individual properties of the object."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:41
msgid "## Signature and Tracking"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:43
msgid "Electronic warfare plays a critical part in combat too through evasion and tracking."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:44
msgid "A ship's signature range represents how well a ship can avoid being tracked by enemy weapons and is 75% of the detection value."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:45
msgid "The value can be further modified by the **Signature Range** modifier of the ship, and decreased by the **Tracking** bonus of the enemy ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:46
msgid "Ships will be able to identify other ships if they are closer than their signature range, otherwise they will be shown an \"Unknown\"."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:48
msgid "Almost all forward weapons have an amount of swivel, which allows them to aim slightly at the target."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:49
msgid "Furthermore, turret weapons can aim the entire 360° and shoot at ships in any directions."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:50
msgid "Weapons try to compensate for target velocities for accurate shots, however, this is reduced based on the signature range of the target ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:51
msgid "In particular, weapons have a minimum tracking range, and maximum tracking range."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:52
msgid "Any ship with a signature range above the maximum tracking range will be aimed at nearly perfectly, barring sudden accelerations."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:53
msgid "On the other hand, any ship with a signature range below the minimum tracking range will not be locked onto, and the shots will aim at the current position, not correcting for velocity."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:54
msgid "For in-between values it will be interpolated linearly."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:56
msgid "Similarly, the lock-on time of launchers is modified by the signature range of the target and tracking values of the launcher."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:57
msgid "If the target has a signature range above the maximum tracking range, the lock-on time will be unmodified."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:58
msgid "If the target has a signature range below the minimum tracking range, it will not be able to lock on."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:59
msgid "Similar to bolt weapons, in-between values will be interpolated linearly."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:61
msgid "## Stealth"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:63
msgid "The stealth range of a ship is based on 25% of the detection range."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:64
msgid "If there are no ships within the stealth range, the ship will be able to enter stealth mode."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:65
msgid "In stealth mode, the ship will be undetectable, however, it will have its [movement](mechanics/movement) significantly reduced."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:66
msgid "In particular, acceleration and turn speed will be reduced by 80%, while maximum speed will be reduced by 50%."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:67
msgid "The minimum range of stealth is <%= constant( \"STEALTH_MIN_DIST\", \"distance\" ) %>, but this can be lowered by being in an asteroid field, being near a jump point, or system interference."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:69
msgid "### Jumping with Stealth"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:71
msgid "When in stealth mode, it is possible to start hyperspace jumps at three times the maximum normal distance from jump points."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:72
msgid "Additionally, when entering a system in stealth mode, the ship will drop out of hyperspace sooner instead of near the jump point."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:73
msgid "Being within <%= constant( \"EW_JUMP_BONUS_RANGE\", \"distance\" ) %> of jump points also lowers the stealth range by 50%, making it significantly easier to stealth."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:75
msgid "## Scanning"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:77
msgid "Like the detection range, the scanning time of a ship is determined by its mass."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:78
msgid "The time it takes to scan a ship is determined by `mass^(1/3) * 1.25`, which amounts to 7.22 seconds for a Llama with 193 tonnes of mass or 22.5 seconds for a Goddard with 5,834 tonnes of mass."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:79
msgid "This value is divided by the **Detection Range** and **Signature Range** values of the ship, and multiplied **Scanned Speed** of the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:81
msgid "## System Modifiers"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:83
msgid "System modifiers such as asteroid fields and interference can further affect electronic warfare."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:84
msgid "In particular, being in an asteroid will affect the detection range, and consequently, signature range and stealth range depending on the density of asteroids."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/ewarfare.md:85
msgid "Furthermore, the system interference will lower signature and stealth ranges, but not the detection range, making it harder to track and identify ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:2
msgid "Psychic Powers and Flow"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:5
msgid "# Psychic Powers and Flow"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:7
msgid "[House Sirius](lore/factions/sirius) is renowned for psychic prowess, however, most psychic powers are very weak and require large amplifiers to maximize the potential."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:8
msgid "Psychic users can use either a ship fabricated by [House Sirius](lore/factions/sirius) or special outfits such as flow amplifiers to enable the use of psychic abilities in space."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:9
msgid "Such psychic abilities can be further enhanced by using meditation chambers and flow resonators to increase the psychic potential."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:11
msgid "When a ship has a psychic amplifier, either built-in or through an outfit, flow will be enabled and visible through the GUI."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:12
msgid "By default, flow will regenerate naturally up to 50% of the natural amount."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:13
msgid "Furthermore, taking damage in the ship will generate flow, although this will decay if over 50% of the maximum amount."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:15
msgid "Flow can be used to activate psychic abilities, which must be acquired, generally through Obelisk trials."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:16
msgid "Abilities can be equipped like normal outfits and bound to [weapon sets](mechanics/weaponsets) to be used."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/flow.md:17
msgid "For each obtained ability, maximum flow will be increased by 5%."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:2
msgid "Hailing"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:4
msgid "# Hailing"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:6
msgid "Communicating with ships or spaceports can be a good way to request assistance, discourage them from attacking your ship through bribing, or even obtaining information."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:7
msgid "You can hail ships in space using the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"hail\")..\"#0\" %> key."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:8
msgid "Additionally, some ships will hail your ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:9
msgid "You can respond to these ships by either targeting them and hailing them, or using the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"autohail\")..\"#0\" %> key to respond directly."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:11
msgid "## Requesting Fuel"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:13
msgid "When you run out of [fuel](mechanics/hyperspace), some good Samaritans will offer to refuel you, usually in exchange for credits."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:14
msgid "If you hail a pilot when you are out of fuel, the option will appear, and you can negotiate to get your ship refueled."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:16
msgid "## Bribing"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:18
msgid "When dealing with hostile ships, you are sometimes able to bribe them and their companions."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:19
msgid "By hailing them, you will get an option to bribe them and also all their fleet members."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:20
msgid "After you make the payment, the hostile ships will turn neutral and leave you alone."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hailing.md:21
msgid "Do note that if you make them angry again, it is likely they will be not as kind as before."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:2
msgid "Heat Management"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:4
msgid "# Heat"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:6
msgid "Most outfits generate heat when used."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:7
msgid "They will heat up, and in turn, heat up the rest of the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:8
msgid "As the temperature goes up, weapons will become increasingly inaccurate and fire at a slower rate."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:9
msgid "Weapons become more inaccurate at over 500 K and have lower fire rate at over 1,100 K."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:11
msgid "## Active Cooldown"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:13
msgid "Although ships cool down naturally through radiation of excess heat, they can perform an active cooldown manoeuvre to dump all excess heat in a short amount of time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:14
msgid "Not only does it get rid of all excess heat, but it will also reload all weapons on the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:15
msgid "The downside is the ship will be immovable and unable to defend itself during this time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:16
msgid "An active cooldown can be performed by either double tapping the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"reverse\")..\"#0\" %> key or by pressing the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"cooldown\")..\"#0\" %> key."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/heat.md:17
msgid "The amount of time it takes to do an active cooldown depends on both the mass of the ship and the amount of excess heat."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hyperspace.md:2
msgid "Hyperspace and Jumping"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hyperspace.md:4
msgid "# Hyperspace and Jumping"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hyperspace.md:6
msgid "Ships can travel from star system to star system through hyperspace by using their built-in hyperdrives."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hyperspace.md:7
msgid "Travelling through hyperspace is called **jumping** and requires fuel specified by the ship being used."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hyperspace.md:8
msgid "Jumping can only be done from systems connected to each other, and must be done near the vicinity of a jump point."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/hyperspace.md:9
msgid "The [universe map](mechanics/map) depicting which systems are connected."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:2
msgid "Landing"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:4
msgid "# Landing"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:6
msgid "Landing on spaceports is one of the fundamental activities you will do while exploring the universe."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:8
msgid "## Landing Window"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:10
msgid "The first window you will be greeted by."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:11
msgid "It contains a description of the spaceport, and some properties of the place you are visited."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:12
msgid "In most spaceports you can also buy a local map and refuel your ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:13
msgid "The services offered by the spaceport will vary significantly."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:15
msgid "### Spaceport Bar"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:17
msgid "The best place to meet other individuals."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:18
msgid "Not only will you be able to chat with the locals, you will also meet other individuals who may offer you missions or other things."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:19
msgid "Important individuals will be marked with an exclamation point."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:20
msgid "Furthermore, the tab will be marked with two exclamation points if an important individual is at the spaceport bar."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:22
msgid "### Missions"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:24
msgid "The Mission Bullet Board System is where you can accept a diversity of different missions."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:25
msgid "The missions offered there are usually a good way to make additional credits or increase your reputation with different factions."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:26
msgid "You can filter the missions based on their legal status, and also sort them based on different properties such as rewards."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:28
msgid "### Outfits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:30
msgid "At the outfitter, you are able to buy locally available outfits, and also sell any outfit you have."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:31
msgid "The availability of outfits depends on the location."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:32
msgid "You can hold #bshift#0 and #bcontrol#0 to increase the amount of outfits you buy or sell at a time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:34
msgid "All the outfits you know and their availability can be accessed [here](outfits)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:36
msgid "### Shipyard"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:38
msgid "Ships can be purchased at the shipyard."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:39
msgid "You have either the option to buy a new ship, or trade in your current ship when buying a new one."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:40
msgid "The new ship will be available at the equipment tab for use after purchase."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:42
msgid "All the ships you know and their availability can be accessed [here](ships)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:44
msgid "### Equipment"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:46
msgid "Any spaceport with refuelling capabilities will allow you to access the [equipment tab](mechanics/equipment)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:47
msgid "Here you can change the outfits on your ships, or change your current ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:49
msgid "By right-clicking on ships, or toggling the #bdeployed#0 checkbox, you can set a ship as part of [your player fleet](mechanics/playerfleet)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:52
msgid "You can click on the slots of the selecting ship to filter only the outfits that go in the slot."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:53
msgid "Right-clicking on a slot will remove an outfit, while right-clicking on an outfit will add it to the slot."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:54
msgid "You can use the tabs and the outfit filter to further control what outfits are visible."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:56
msgid "### Commodity Exchange"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:58
msgid "Here you can buy or sell commodities."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:59
msgid "The price will depend on the location, which you can compare on [the universe map](mechanics/map)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:60
msgid "By buying low and selling high, you can turn quite a profit."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/landing.md:61
msgid "Similarly to the outfitter, you can hold #bshift#0 and #bcontrol#0 to increase the amount of commodities you buy or sell at a time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:2
msgid "Launchers"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:4
msgid "# Launchers"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:6
msgid "Launcher weapons differ from bolt and beam weapons by needing ammunition to function."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:7
msgid "They come in made different shapes and sizes, from slow and devastating seek torpedoes, to fast and agile dumbfire rockets."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:8
msgid "Like other outfits they can be equipped using [weapon sets](mechanics/weaponsets) and will be set to primary or secondary groups by default."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:10
msgid "## Types"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:12
msgid "Launchers are roughly divided into three categories:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:13
msgid "1. **Torpedoes** are slow and devastating and are able to significantly damage even the largest of ships, however, they do not pose a threat to ships with mobility."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:14
msgid "2. **Missiles** are fast and agile, meant for targeting smaller ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:15
msgid "3. **Dumbfires** have no tracking ability, however, they usually pack a higher payload than other weapons of the same size."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:17
msgid "## Ammunition"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:19
msgid "Unlike other weapons, launchers use ammunition."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:20
msgid "They have a maximum amount of ammunition that they can hold, and will slowly regenerate ammunition over time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:21
msgid "Ammunition can be fully regenerated by performing an active [cooldown](mechanics/heat) and is also regenerated when landing."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:23
msgid "## Lock-On and Calibration"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:25
msgid "Seeking launchers have both a **Lock-On** and **In-flight Calibration** time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:26
msgid "**Lock-On** refers to how long it takes to obtain a lock on your current target, and takes an amount of time based on the launcher itself, and the [signature](mechanics/ewarfare) of your target."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:27
msgid "Until the launchers gets a lock-on, you will not be able to fire it."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:28
msgid "The lock-on status can be seen by an icon on the weapon in the GUI and will turn into a cross-hair when locked on."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:30
msgid "**In-flight Calibration** refers to the time it takes for the launched munition to start tracking the target."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:31
msgid "A circle will slowly appear around the launched munition when it begins in-flight calibration."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:32
msgid "When it starts tracking, the circle will disappear and the munition will begin accelerating and turning towards its target."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:33
msgid "Note that even when not calibrated, the munition will be able to hit its target."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:35
msgid "## Jamming"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:37
msgid "Each seeking launcher can have **Jam Resistance** allowing it to avoid being jammed by the target it is tracking."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:38
msgid "If the target has **Jamming**, once the munition is in the target's [signature range](mechanics/ewarfare), it will either get jammed or not."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:39
msgid "The chance of getting jammed is `Jamming - Jam Resistance`."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:40
msgid "If the munition is jammed, it can be affected by one of the following effects:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:41
msgid "1. **Slowed:** the munition will move up to half as fast but still track."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:42
msgid "2. **Guidance Jammed:** the munition will either go straight forward or endlessly loop either to the left or right."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:43
msgid "3. **Self-Destruct:** the munition will blow up."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:45
msgid "## Point Defense"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:47
msgid "Some launcher munitions are susceptible to point defense weapons and will have **Armour** and **Absorption** stats like ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:48
msgid "Point defense systems will be able to damage these munitions, and they will explode if they take a total of damage over the amount of armour they have."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/launchers.md:49
msgid "See [damage](mechanics/damage) for how the damage is computed."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:2
msgid "Star Map"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:4
msgid "# Map"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:6
msgid "The map can be opened by the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"starmap\")..\"#0\" %> key and gives in-depth information about the explored universe."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:7
msgid "By default, the map shows in-depth information including dominant faction of the systems, local system features, the nebula, and more."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:8
msgid "What the map shows can be toggled with the different map modes."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:10
msgid "## Autonav"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:12
msgid "When clicking on a system in the map, the shortest autonav route from the current position is selected."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:13
msgid "The bold green line indicates the next jump, bold yellow lines indicate subsequent jumps you still have fuel for, and bold red lines indicate jumps you will no longer have enough fuel to perform."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:14
msgid "By clicking the \"Autonav\" button at the bottom, you can directly start autonav and close the map."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:16
msgid "If you wish to manually create a route, by holding the #bshift#0 key while clicking, you can add routes from your current selected system."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:17
msgid "This allows you to manually create your autonav route as you wish."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:19
msgid "## Notes"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:21
msgid "You can leave notes on the current selected system using the \"Toggle Note\" button at the bottom."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:22
msgid "This lets you mark and write things about interesting systems you have explored or other local properties."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:23
msgid "The information will be available whenever you open the map."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:24
msgid "You can delete added notes by selecting the system and pressing the \"Toggle Note\" button again."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:26
msgid "## Modes"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:28
msgid "The map offers several modes to explore all the information it offers."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:30
msgid "The \"Discovery\" mode indicates if you still have things to find in a system, such as space objects, or jump points."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:31
msgid "Systems that are marked in green are fully explored, and you can find nothing new with your current sensors."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:33
msgid "The commodity modes show the absolute cost and relative price (trade) with respect to the current system on the map."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:34
msgid "Both the cost mode and trade mode are available for all the standard commodities you can trade for."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:36
msgid "Finally, the \"Minimal Mode\" button toggles a simplified view of the map, without all the overlays for easier interpretation."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:38
msgid "## Find"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:40
msgid "The \"Find\" button at the button at the bottom can be used to find systems, space objects, outfits, or ships from text."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:41
msgid "This will list all found partial matches in descending order of distance, and can be used to find things easily."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/map.md:42
msgid "As an alternative, the [outfits](outfits) and [ships](ships) that you know about and their locations can also be explored on the Archives."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:2
msgid "Mass"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:4
msgid "# Mass"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:6
msgid "Mass plays an important role for a ship's [movement](mechanics/movement) and [electronic warfare](mechanics/ewarfare)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:7
msgid "All ships have an inherent mass that is increased by outfits and cargo."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:8
msgid "As the mass increases, a ship's [visibility and signature](mechanics/ewarfare) will increase, making it easier to detect and attack."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:9
msgid "Furthermore, ships have a mass limit, determined by the core engine."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mass.md:10
msgid "If the ship's mass surpasses the mass limit, it will suffer penalties to [movement](mechanics/movement)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:2
msgid "Mining"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:4
msgid "# Mining"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:6
msgid "Many valuable resources are hidden in the asteroids that can be found across space."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:7
msgid "While it is possible to just blow up asteroids with standard weapons, this gives low yields and does not allow extracting fragile resources."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:8
msgid "In order to obtain the most out of mining, it is necessary to be prepared and use outfits specialized for mining."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:10
msgid "## Finding Asteroids"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:12
msgid "Asteroids can be found throughout space."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:13
msgid "While asteroids near heavily civilized areas are easier to access, they tend to be over-mined and have fewer rare resources remaining."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:14
msgid "On the other hand, asteroid fields in forgotten or dangerous areas tend to have higher yields."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:15
msgid "It is important to scout out the asteroid field first to see what resources can be available."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:17
msgid "## Asteroid Rarity"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:19
msgid "Each asteroid field will have its own distribution of asteroids which can be of three different levels of rarity:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:20
msgid "1. **Common**: These asteroids contain not very valuable minerals such as iron or nickel."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:21
msgid "1. **Uncommon**: These contain more valuable minerals such as gold or platinum."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:22
msgid "1. **Rare**: Hard to find but contain very expensive and rare minerals that fetch high prices on the market and are widely sought out."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:24
msgid "## Mining Outfits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:26
msgid "Outfits play a critical role in mining."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:27
msgid "Although normal weapons can be used, they tend to be too destructive to effectively mine."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:28
msgid "There are two major groups of mining gear: mining beams, and mining drills."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:30
msgid "The outfits have several important properties:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:31
msgid "* **Mining Bonus**: Multiplies the yield obtained by mining, but does not change the type of mineral being mined."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:32
msgid "* **Asteroid Scanner Range**: Defines the range at which asteroids will be scanned for their contents. Asteroids are classified into either \"common\", \"uncommon\", or \"rare\" depending on what they can contain."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:33
msgid "* **Ability to mine uncommon and rare minerals**: Normal weapons are only able to mine common minerals. On the other hand, specialized weapons and outfits can mine uncommon and even rare minerals from asteroids."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:35
msgid "### Mining Beams"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:37
msgid "Mining beams are specialized in destroying asteroids."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:38
msgid "They tend to have high penetration and low range, but allow obtaining larger yields and rarer minerals."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:40
msgid "### Mining Drills"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:42
msgid "Mining drills are utility outfits that can be activated near a selected asteroid to efficiently extract minerals."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/mining.md:43
msgid "They require precise manual control but have the highest yields and success rates of the mining outfits."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:2
msgid "Missions"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:4
msgid "# Missions"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:6
msgid "Many different factions and individuals will offer you missions where you can help them in exchange for rewards."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:7
msgid "Although missions can be offered in many forms, such as by [hailing ships](mechanics/hailing), or [boarding](mechanics/boarding) derelicts, most missions you will come across will be offered either from the Mission Bulletin Board System or the Spaceport Bar."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:9
msgid "## Mission Bulletin Board System"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:11
msgid "Although not available on all spaceports, the Mission Bullet Board System is the fastest way to find missions to do."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:12
msgid "All available missions will be directly listed with all details, including rewards, in each posting."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:13
msgid "Missions can also be sorted and filtered via the gear button in the top right."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:15
msgid "Doing missions for factions is both a good way to make [credits](mechanics/credits) and to increase your [reputation](mechanics/reputation)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:17
msgid "## Spaceport Bar"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:19
msgid "All sorts of characters will pop up in the Spaceport Bar, from locals who may give you hints or tips, to people who have jobs or services for you."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:20
msgid "Particularly important characters will have a red exclamation mark at the top and appear at the beginning of the bar."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:21
msgid "Additionally, if there is an important character, the bar tab will have red exclamation marks highlighting it."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/missions.md:22
msgid "Helping characters is a good way to access new things and make yourself known in the universe."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:2
msgid "Movement in Space"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:4
msgid "# Movement"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:6
msgid "Ship movement in space is Newtonian-based where ships can accelerate with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"accel\")..\"#0\" %> key and turn with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"left\")..\"#0\" %> and <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"right\")..\"#0\" %> keys."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:7
msgid "The ships will drift without friction unless they surpass their maximum speed, which will slow down the ship until it returns to the maximum speed."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:9
msgid "## Afterburners and Other Movement Outfits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:11
msgid "Movement outfits can be useful for getting away or chasing down other ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:12
msgid "While outfits may be bound to [weapon sets](mechanics/weaponsets) to use them, most movement outfits can also be triggered by double tapping acceleration with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"accel\")..\"#0\" %> key."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/movement.md:13
msgid "Furthermore, if supported, double tapping turn with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"left\")..\"#0\" %> and <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"right\")..\"#0\" %> keys."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:2
msgid "Fleets"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:5
msgid "# Fleets"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:7
msgid "Besides your own ship, it is possible to deploy and command a fleet of ships when out in space."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:8
msgid "You can deploy any ship you own as a fleet member, as long as it is space worthy by right-clicking on them or toggling the deployed checkbox."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:9
msgid "The amount of ships you can deploy deeps on your **fleet capacity**."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:10
msgid "Each ship, including your own, requires a certain amount of **fleet capacity**."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:11
msgid "The total sum of fleet capacity from your deployed ships may not surpass your **fleet capacity**."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/playerfleet.md:12
msgid "When deployed ships are destroyed, they will regenerate the next time you land."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:2
msgid "Reputation"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:4
msgid "# Reputation"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:6
msgid "Reputation represents how well you are liked by each [faction](lore/factions)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:7
msgid "Increasing your reputation with a specific faction can give you access to more of their [outfits](outfits), [ships](ships), and spaceports."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:8
msgid "With sufficient reputation, a faction will see you as friendly, changing how their ships behave near you."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:9
msgid "On the other hand, lowering your reputation can lead to a faction seeing you as an enemy, barring you from their spaceports and attacking you on sight."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:11
msgid "Your reputation is on a per-system basis, however, neighbouring systems of the same faction will have a tendency to be similar."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:12
msgid "By default, you will get a message whenever there is a reputation change, but you can modify this from the settings in the #binformation window#0 that you can open with the <%= \"#b\"..naev.keyGet(\"info\")..\"#0\" %> key."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:13
msgid "Your current global reputation standings and other details of the different factions can also be seen from the #bInformation window#0."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:15
msgid "## Changing Reputation"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:17
msgid "There are several ways to change your reputation with a faction:"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:19
msgid "1. [Doing missions](mechanics/missions)"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:20
msgid "1. Attacking, [boarding](mechanics/boarding), or destroying ships"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:22
msgid "Reputation changes will propagate to allies and enemies of the faction your reputation is changing with."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:23
msgid "For example, although attacking a faction will decrease your standing with them, attacking an enemy of a faction will increase your standing with them."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:25
msgid "## Reputation Limits"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:27
msgid "Each faction has a maximum level of reputation you can reach."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/reputation.md:28
msgid "This maximum will be increased as you perform specific [missions](mechanics/missions) for the faction."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:2
msgid "Ship Stats"
msgstr ""


#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:4
msgid "# Ship Stats"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:6
msgid "There are many different important stats for ships that define their behaviour when flying in space."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:7
msgid "These are all visible from the [equipment](mechanics/equipment) panel."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:8
msgid "The final ship stats are defined based on the intrinsic ship stats, equipped outfits, and other sources such as temporary effects."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:10
msgid "## Core Stats"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:12
msgid "The core stats define basic properties of the ship."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:14
msgid "* [Model](ships): The name of the ship model."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:15
msgid "* [Class](ships/classes): The ship class."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:16
msgid "* [Value](mechanics/credits): The value of the ship including all the [outfits](outfits) equipped on it."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:18
msgid "* [Fleet Capacity](mechanics/playerfleet): Determine how much fleet capacity a ship uses when deployed in a [fleet](mechanics/playerfleet)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:20
msgid "* [Crew](mechanics/boarding): The crew the ship has. This plays a role when [boarding](mechanics/boarding) other ships."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:22
msgid "## Movement Stats"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:24
msgid "Movement is based on Newtonian physics, however, ships have a maximum speed limit when acceleration is not being applied."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:26
msgid "* [Mass](mechanics/movement): How heavy the ship is. If the mass of a ship goes over the [mass limit](mechanics/mass) of the engine, it will receive a penalty to [movement](mechanics/movement)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:27
msgid "* [Jump Time](mechanics/time): Determines how much [time](mechanics/time) it takes for the ship to go through [hyperspace](mechanics/hyperspace)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:28
msgid "* [Accel](mechanics/movement): Specifies how fast a ship can accelerate. While accelerating, a ship can go over the [max speed](mechanics/movement)."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:29
msgid "* [Speed](mechanics/movement): Determines the max speed of the ship when not accelerating."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:30
msgid "* [Turn](mechanics/movement): Specifies how fast the ship can rotate."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:31
msgid "* [Time Constant](mechanics/movement): Determines how fast time feels like it is moving. A value of 100% indicates that time progresses normally, a value of 120% would indicate that 1.2 seconds of game time happen in 1 second of real time."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:33
msgid "## Electronic Warfare"
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:35
msgid "Electronic warfare determines how ships see and target each other."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:37
msgid "* [Detected at](mechanics/ewarfare): The distance at which the ship will be detected without detection bonuses."
msgstr ""

#: dat/naevpedia/mechanics/shipstats.md:38
